{"title_page": "Classical Public Radio Network", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=October 2013}}\n{{Update|date=January 2011}}\nThe '''Classical Public Radio Network''' was a national, 24-hour classical music service in the United States. Its mission was to preserve, enhance and expand experience of classical music for radio listeners.  With this vision, CPRN was established in 1998 as a limited-liability non-profit company \u2013 a joint venture of [[KUSC]] (Los Angeles) and [[Colorado Public Radio]] \u2013 with startup funding from the [[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]]. In 2003, CPRN and [[National Public Radio]] (NPR) joined in a collaborative marketing arrangement to further expand the network, but ceased national broadcast operations on June 30, 2008.\n\nCPRN offered listeners the full spectrum of the classical repertoire from medieval times to the present \u2013 complete symphonies and orchestral pieces, chamber works, opera selections, art songs, and choral works. The announcers and music staff programmed the music with a focus on core repertoire and superior recordings. Each announcer brought personal expertise to selecting featured music, alternate performances, artist tributes and unique recordings, as well as seasonal and date-specific programming.\n\nEnhancing the 24-hour program stream were several weekly and daily shows and features. Weekdays, Kimberlea Daggy hosted ''The Daily Special'' at noon, and Charles Andrews unearthed ''Buried Treasures'' at 8:00pm. On Sunday mornings, Stephanie Wendt presented ''Sacred Classics'', featuring three hours of meditative music for the heart and mind. Contemporary classical music was explored every Saturday evening by Alan Chapman on ''Modern Masterpieces''. The programming was regularly enhanced with holiday programming, new releases, composer profiles, and frequent appearances by artists in the classical music world.\n\nCPRN programming was carried across the country on the following public radio stations: [[KUSC]], Los Angeles; [[KVOD]], Denver; [[WBHM]], Birmingham, Alabama; [[KBSU-FM]], Boise, Idaho; [[South Dakota Public Broadcasting]], Vermillion, South Dakota; High Plains Public Radio, Garden City, Kansas ([[KANZ]]) and Amarillo, Texas ([[KJJP]]); [[KBYI]], Rexburg, Idaho; [[KWTU]], Tulsa, Oklahoma; [[WTEB]], New Bern, North Carolina; [[WFCR]], Amherst, Massachusetts; [[WOSU-FM]], Columbus, Ohio; and on digital radio, [[WHYY-FM]], Philadelphia, Pennsylvania; [[WJCT-FM]], Jacksonville, Florida; and  [[KDFC-FM]], San Francisco.\n\nFormer client stations operated a total of 53 signals and reached more than one million listeners weekly. Programming was distributed to stations via the [[Public Radio Satellite System]].\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061005231904/http://www.classicalradio.org/ CPRN website]\n\n[[Category:American radio networks]]\n[[Category:Public radio in the United States]]\n[[Category:Programs of the University of Southern California]]\n[[Category:Classical music radio stations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=October 2013}}\n{{Update|date=January 2011}}\nThe '''Classical Public Radio Network''' was a national, 24-hour classical music service in the United States. Its mission was to preserve, enhance and expand experience of classical music for radio listeners.  With this vision, CPRN was established in 1998 as a limited-liability non-profit company \u2013 a joint venture of [[KUSC]] (Los Angeles) and [[Colorado Public Radio]] \u2013 with startup funding from the [[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]]. In 2003, CPRN and [[National Public Radio]] (NPR) joined in a collaborative marketing arrangement to further expand the network, but ceased national broadcast operations on June 30, 2008.\n\nCPRN offered listeners the full spectrum of the classical repertoire from medieval times to the present \u2013 complete symphonies and orchestral pieces, chamber works, opera selections, art songs, and choral works. The announcers and music staff programmed the music with a focus on core repertoire and superior recordings. Each announcer brought personal expertise to selecting featured music, alternate performances, artist tributes and unique recordings, as well as seasonal and date-specific programming.\n\nEnhancing the 24-hour program stream were several weekly and daily shows and features. Weekdays, Kimberlea Daggy hosted ''The Daily Special'' at noon, and Charles Andrews unearthed ''Buried Treasures'' at 8:00pm. On Sunday mornings, Stephanie Wendt presented ''Sacred Classics'', featuring three hours of meditative music for the heart and mind. Contemporary classical music was explored every Saturday evening by Alan Chapman on ''Modern Masterpieces''. The programming was regularly enhanced with holiday programming, new releases, composer profiles, and frequent appearances by artists in the classical music world.\n\nCPRN programming was carried across the country on the following public radio stations: [[KUSC]], Los Angeles; [[KVOD]], Denver; [[WBHM]], Birmingham, Alabama; [[KBSU-FM]], Boise, Idaho; [[South Dakota Public Broadcasting]], Vermillion, South Dakota; High Plains Public Radio, Garden City, Kansas ([[KANZ]]) and Amarillo, Texas ([[KJJP]]); [[KBYI]], Rexburg, Idaho; [[KWTU]], Tulsa, Oklahoma; [[WTEB]], New Bern, North Carolina; [[WFCR]], Amherst, Massachusetts; [[WOSU-FM]], Columbus, Ohio; and on digital radio, [[WHYY-FM]], Philadelphia, Pennsylvania,  [[WJCT-FM]], Jacksonville, Florida, and  [[KDFC-FM]], San Francisco.\n\nFormer client stations operated a total of 53 signals and reached more than one million listeners weekly. Programming was distributed to stations via the [[Public Radio Satellite System]].\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061005231904/http://www.classicalradio.org/ CPRN website]\n\n[[Category:American radio networks]]\n[[Category:Public radio in the United States]]\n[[Category:Programs of the University of Southern California]]\n[[Category:Classical music radio stations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Stereorock", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_Public_Radio_Network"}
{"title_page": "Tom Fitton", "text_new": "{{short description|American activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tom Fitton\n| image              = Tom Fitton by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| alt                = Tom Fitton\n| caption            = Fitton in December 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|05|30}}\n| birth_place        = [[West Nyack, New York]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[George Washington University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| organization       = [[Judicial Watch]]\n| occupation         = [[Activist]]\n}}\n\n'''Thomas J. Fitton''' (born May 30, 1968) is the president of [[Judicial Watch]], an American [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] activist group.\n\nFitton is prominent for criticizing [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel Robert Mueller]]'s investigation into [[Russian interference]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election]]; he has claimed that the investigation is a \"coup\" against U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] and called for it to be shut down.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFitton [[Climate change denial|rejects]] the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]; under his tenure, Judicial Watch has filed lawsuits against [[List of climate scientists|climate scientists]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":52\" />\n\n==Early life==\nFitton was born in [[West Nyack, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/transcript/?id=8526|title=Q&A with Tom Fitton|publisher=C-SPAN|date=May 19, 2009|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> He graduated from [[Clarkstown High School South]] in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyjnews.com/celebrations/announce_details.php?type=W&id=C6366645|title=lohud.com {{!}} Celebrations {{!}} The Journal News|website=www.nyjnews.com|access-date=2019-05-02}}</ref> Fitton has a bachelor's degree in English from [[George Washington University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/people/3729634-thomas-fitton|title=Thomas Fitton, Judicial Watch Inc: Profile & Biography|website=Bloomberg}}</ref> His father was a manager at a supermarket and his mother was a nurse.<ref>Neil NcCabe Washington Examiner</ref>\n\n==Judicial Watch==\nFitton has been President of Judicial Watch since August 1998. The group primarily seeks access to government records, filing [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] (FOIA) and other public records act lawsuits, and engaging in other forms of civil litigation.\n\nIn 2006, [[Larry Klayman]], Judicial Watch's former Chairman, attempted to reclaim control of Judicial Watch by suing Fitton, the organization, and the organization's other officers and directors. Most of Klayman's claims, including all of the claims against Fitton and Judicial Watch's other officers and directors, were dismissed in 2009.<ref>''Klayman v. Judicial Watch, Inc.'', 628 F. Supp.2d 112, 118 (D.D.C. 2009).</ref>\n\n==Views==\n\n=== Zimmerman trial===\n\nIn July 2013, Fitton falsely claimed that the Obama administration's Department of Justice had sent representatives to [[Sanford, Florida]] following Martin's death \"to help organize and manage rallies and protests against George Zimmerman.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2013/jul/12/judicial-watch/judicial-watch-says-department-justice-unit-organi/|title=Judicial Watch says Department of Justice unit organized protests against George Zimmerman|date=July 12, 2013|publisher=PolitiFact}}</ref> \n\n=== Climate change ===\nFitton rejects the scientific consensus on climate change ([[global warming]]).<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/feb/22/climate-change-science-attacks-threats-trump|title=Climate scientists face harassment, threats and fears of 'McCarthyist attacks'|last=Milman|first=Oliver|date=2017-02-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He has said \"There has been scandal after scandal involving climate data and we are skeptical of government agencies that won\u2019t tell people what they are up to... I\u2019m sure scientists are concerned that funding for dubious research will be cut, but the truth will win out in the end.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Judicial Watch, which has claimed that [[climate science]] is \"fraud science\", has filed lawsuits seeking to force the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA)&nbsp;to release the correspondence of climate scientists who published a 2015 study in the [[Science (journal)|journal ''Science'']].<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite news|url=https://insideclimatenews.org/news/16012017/climate-change-noaa-donald-trump-lamar-smith-global-warming-hiatus|title=Climate scientists battle attacks on their research from conservatives, brace for more under Trump|date=2017-02-06|work=InsideClimate News|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-consensus-97-per-cent/2016/jul/07/climate-scientists-are-under-attack-from-frivolous-lawsuits|title=Climate scientists are under attack from frivolous lawsuits {{!}} Lauren Kurtz|last=Kurtz|first=Lauren|date=2016-07-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The study had debunked one of the common claims made by those who reject the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]], namely that there existed [[Global warming hiatus|global warming \"hiatus\"]] between 1998\u20132012.<ref name=\":52\" /> The [[Climate Science Legal Defense Fund]] (CSLDF), [[American Meteorological Society]] and [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] condemned Judicial Watch, saying that the disclosure of private communications between scientists \"would harm (or halt altogether) government scientists' ability to collaborate with colleagues, damage the government's ability to recruit or retain top scientists, and deter critically important research into politically charged fields like climate change\".<ref name=\":52\" /> The Judicial Watch lawsuit was inspired by Rep. [[Lamar Smith]] who accused the authors of the study of \"alter[ing] data\" to \"get the politically correct results they want.\"<ref name=\":52\" />\n\n=== Support for Breitbart News ===\nJudicial Watch has advertised for years on [[Breitbart News]], the far-right website formerly run by [[Steve Bannon]].<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2017/06/08/breitbart-lost-90-percent-of-its-advertisers-in-two-months-whos-still-there/|title=Breitbart lost 90 percent of its advertisers in two months: Who\u2019s still there?|last=Bhattarai|first=Abha|date=2017-06-08|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> The site was defended by Fitton against calls for advertisers to drop them for advertising. Fitton stated, \"Liberal activists want to destroy Breitbart, but we won\u2019t be cowed\".<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Voter fraud ===\nFitton said about [[Voter impersonation (United States)|voter fraud]]: \"We have all heard about voter fraud and the attempts by liberal media organs like the&nbsp;''New York Times''&nbsp;and Ivory Tower academics to dismiss it as a nonexistent problem. But it is real, widespread, and substantial to the point that it can decide elections\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Clean House: Exposing Our Government's Secrets and Lies|last=Fitton|first=Tom|publisher=Threshold Editions|year=2016|isbn=978-1501137051|location=New York|page=117}}</ref> Fitton has alleged that hundreds of thousands of undocumented immigrants voted in the 2018 mid-term elections.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/05/28/resignation-texas-is-reminder-how-trumps-vote-fraud-claims-come-up-empty/|title=A resignation in Texas is a reminder of how Trump\u2019s vote-fraud claims come up empty|last=|first=|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> There is  evidence of widespread voter fraud in California and  Texas.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/california/statements/2019/jun/24/donald-trump/pants-fire-trumps-latest-california-voter-fraud-cl/|title=Trump\u2019s latest California voter fraud claim is Pants on Fire|website=@politifact|language=en|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/24/politics/fact-check-trump-voter-fraud-california/index.html|title=Trump makes yet another false claim about California voter fraud|author=Daniel Dale|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2020, the day of the [[Iowa caucuses]] in the Democratic presidential primary, Fitton suggested that voter fraud was afoot in Iowa by claiming that \u201ceight Iowa counties have more voter registrations than citizens old enough to register.\u201d Iowa's Secretary of State, Paul Pate, a member of the Republican Party, debunked Fitton's claim by linking to official voter registration data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2020/02/03/election-2020-iowa-caucus-problems/4618371002/|title=The misinformation campaign: Iowa SOS blasts Judicial Watch for insinuating voter fraud|last=Clayworth|first=Jason|website=Des Moines Register|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/02/03/conservatives-push-false-claims-voter-fraud-twitter-iowans-prepare-caucus/|title=Conservatives push false claims of voter fraud on Twitter as Iowans prepare to caucus|last=|first=|date=2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Russian interference in the 2016 election ===\n{{main|Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections}}\nIn 2017, Judicial Watch helped to stoke Republican attacks against Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]]'s investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/no-longer-a-lonely-battle-how-the-campaign-against-the-mueller-probe-has-taken-hold/2017/12/24/441fc726-e5cb-11e7-a65d-1ac0fd7f097e_story.html|title=No longer a \u2018lonely battle\u2019: How the campaign against the Mueller probe has taken hold|last=Kranish|first=Michael|date=2017-12-24|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-03-19|last2=Barrett|first2=Devlin|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|last3=Demirjian|first3=Karoun}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/08/07/trump-mueller-attack-judicial-watch-765081|title='I know that he listens to Tom': Meet Trump's anti-Mueller ally|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en}}</ref> He has referred to the Mueller probe as a \"coup\" against Trump.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/apr/29/donald-trump/was-donald-trump-target-coup-no/|title=Was Donald Trump the target of a coup? No|website=@politifact|language=en|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-twitter-video-removed-deleted-2020-russia-mueller-batman-a8862816.html|title=Trump has video removed after rambling late-night Twitter storm about conspiracy theories and immigrants|date=2019-04-10|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> Trump retweeted Fitton's remarks about a coup; PolitiFact rated the assertion that the Mueller probe was a coup as \"pants-on-fire\" false.<ref name=\":2\" /> Trump frequently listens to Fitton and had mentioned Fitton at least five times in his tweets by August 2018, including a promotion of an upcoming Fitton appearance on Fox.<ref name=\":Fitton called for the Special Counsel investigation to be shut down, arguing that prosecutors in the probe were too biased against President Trump to conduct a credible investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/republicans-hammer-mueller-fbi-as-russia-investigation-intensifies/2017/12/06/4a6097ca-dabb-11e7-b1a8-62589434a581_story.html|title=Republicans hammer Mueller, FBI as Russia investigation intensifies|last=Barrett|first=Devlin|date=2017-12-06|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-03-19|last2=Sullivan|first2=Sean|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Fitton furthermore called for shutting down the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)]] \"because it was turned into a KGB-type operation by the Obama administration.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/364868-conservative-watchdog-head-we-need-to-consider-shutting-down-the-fbi|title=Conservative watchdog head: Do we need to shut down the FBI?|last=Anapol|first=Avery|date=December 14, 2017|newspaper=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/us/politics/trump-blames-justice-department-and-fbi-for-conduct-he-says-was-a-disgrace.html|title=Trump Calls Justice Department and F.B.I. Conduct \u2018a Disgrace\u2019|last=Davis|first=Julie Hirschfeld|date=2018-02-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-03-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> ''Newsweek'' rated the claim \"false\", stating that \"there is no comparison between the FBI and KGB.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/fact-check-did-fbi-become-kgb-type-operation-under-obama-748144|title=We fact-checked a Fox News guest's claim that Obama turned the FBI into the KGB|date=2017-12-14|work=Newsweek|access-date=2017-12-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]], Trump's former personal attorney, [[Criminal charges brought in the Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|pleaded guilty to crimes]] brought to light by Special Counsel Robert Mueller's probe in December 2018, Fitton dismissed the importance of the crimes. Fitton said it was \"weak tea\" and intended \"to make President Trump look bad.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/12/conservative-response-michael-cohen-guilty-plea|title=\"It's Weak Tea\": For MAGA Super-Fans, Trump's Legal Nightmare is more fake news|last=Nguyen|first=Tina|date=December 12, 2018|work=Vanity Fair|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Coronavirus pandemic, 2020 ===\nDuring the coronavirus pandemic, Fitton called on President Trump to \"reopen\" the United States amid social distancing and lockdowns to prevent spread of the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/conservative-medias-new-coronavirus-plan-reopen-the-country|title=Conservative Media\u2019s New Coronavirus Plan: Reopen The Country, No Matter Who Dies|website=BuzzFeed News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}As Trump signals readiness to break with experts, his online base assails Fauci|date=2020|work=The Washington Ponews|last=Singh|first=Maanvi|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/01/dr-fauci-security-reportedly-expanded-as-infectious-disease-expert-faces-threats|title=Dr Fauci: security reportedly expanded as infectious disease expert faces threats|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/490725-fauci-given-security-detail-after-receiving-threats|title=Fauci given security detail after receiving threats|last=Zilbermints|first=Regina|date=2020-04-01|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nFitton received the [[American Conservative Union]]'s 'Defender of the Constitution Award' during its annual [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in 2015.<ref>{{cite press release |author=Ross Hemminger |title=Tom Fitton Presented with the Defender of the Constitution Award  |url=http://conservative.org/tom-fitton-presented-with-the-defender-of-the-constitution-award/|location=National Harbor, MD |publisher=American Conservative Union |date=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book|last=Fitton|first=Tom|date=2014|title=The Corruption Chronicles: Obama's Big Secrecy, Big Corruption, and Big Government|isbn=978-1-4767-6705-5|publisher=Threshold Editions| location = New York}}\n* Fitton, Tom ''Clean House: Exposing Our Government's Secrets and Lies'' (New York: Threshold Editions, 2016).  {{ISBN|978-1-5011-3704-4}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.judicialwatch.org/ Judicial Watch homepage]\n* {{C-SPAN|tomfitton}}\n* [http://www.c-span.org/video/?286474-1/qa-tom-fitton Q & A with Tom Fitton, May 19, 2009]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitton, Tom}}\n\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:Columbian College of Arts and Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:People from West Nyack, New York]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tom Fitton\n| image              = Tom Fitton by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| alt                = Tom Fitton\n| caption            = Fitton in December 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1968|05|30}}\n| birth_place        = [[West Nyack, New York]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[George Washington University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| organization       = [[Judicial Watch]]\n| occupation         = [[Activist]]\n}}\n\n'''Thomas J. Fitton''' (born May 30, 1968) is the president of [[Judicial Watch]], an American [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] activist group.\n\nFitton is prominent for criticizing [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel Robert Mueller]]'s investigation into [[Russian interference]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election]]; he has claimed that the investigation is a \"coup\" against U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] and called for it to be shut down.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFitton [[Climate change denial|rejects]] the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]; under his tenure, Judicial Watch has filed lawsuits against [[List of climate scientists|climate scientists]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":52\" />\n\n==Early life==\nFitton was born in [[West Nyack, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/transcript/?id=8526|title=Q&A with Tom Fitton|publisher=C-SPAN|date=May 19, 2009|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> He graduated from [[Clarkstown High School South]] in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyjnews.com/celebrations/announce_details.php?type=W&id=C6366645|title=lohud.com {{!}} Celebrations {{!}} The Journal News|website=www.nyjnews.com|access-date=2019-05-02}}</ref> Fitton has a bachelor's degree in English from [[George Washington University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/people/3729634-thomas-fitton|title=Thomas Fitton, Judicial Watch Inc: Profile & Biography|website=Bloomberg}}</ref> His father was a manager at a supermarket and his mother was a nurse.<ref>Neil NcCabe Washington Examiner</ref>\n\n==Judicial Watch==\nFitton has been President of Judicial Watch since August 1998. The group primarily seeks access to government records, filing [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] (FOIA) and other public records act lawsuits, and engaging in other forms of civil litigation.\n\nIn 2006, [[Larry Klayman]], Judicial Watch's former Chairman, attempted to reclaim control of Judicial Watch by suing Fitton, the organization, and the organization's other officers and directors. Most of Klayman's claims, including all of the claims against Fitton and Judicial Watch's other officers and directors, were dismissed in 2009.<ref>''Klayman v. Judicial Watch, Inc.'', 628 F. Supp.2d 112, 118 (D.D.C. 2009).</ref>\n\n==Views==\n\n=== Zimmerman trial===\n\nIn July 2013, Fitton falsely claimed that the Obama administration's Department of Justice had sent representatives to [[Sanford, Florida]] following Martin's death \"to help organize and manage rallies and protests against George Zimmerman.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2013/jul/12/judicial-watch/judicial-watch-says-department-justice-unit-organi/|title=Judicial Watch says Department of Justice unit organized protests against George Zimmerman|date=July 12, 2013|publisher=PolitiFact}}</ref> \n\n=== Climate change ===\nFitton rejects the scientific consensus on climate change ([[global warming]]).<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/feb/22/climate-change-science-attacks-threats-trump|title=Climate scientists face harassment, threats and fears of 'McCarthyist attacks'|last=Milman|first=Oliver|date=2017-02-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He has said \"There has been scandal after scandal involving climate data and we are skeptical of government agencies that won\u2019t tell people what they are up to... I\u2019m sure scientists are concerned that funding for dubious research will be cut, but the truth will win out in the end.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Judicial Watch, which has claimed that [[climate science]] is \"fraud science\", has filed lawsuits seeking to force the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA)&nbsp;to release the correspondence of climate scientists who published a 2015 study in the [[Science (journal)|journal ''Science'']].<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite news|url=https://insideclimatenews.org/news/16012017/climate-change-noaa-donald-trump-lamar-smith-global-warming-hiatus|title=Climate scientists battle attacks on their research from conservatives, brace for more under Trump|date=2017-02-06|work=InsideClimate News|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-consensus-97-per-cent/2016/jul/07/climate-scientists-are-under-attack-from-frivolous-lawsuits|title=Climate scientists are under attack from frivolous lawsuits {{!}} Lauren Kurtz|last=Kurtz|first=Lauren|date=2016-07-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The study had debunked one of the common claims made by those who reject the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]], namely that there existed [[Global warming hiatus|global warming \"hiatus\"]] between 1998\u20132012.<ref name=\":52\" /> The [[Climate Science Legal Defense Fund]] (CSLDF), [[American Meteorological Society]] and [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] condemned Judicial Watch, saying that the disclosure of private communications between scientists \"would harm (or halt altogether) government scientists' ability to collaborate with colleagues, damage the government's ability to recruit or retain top scientists, and deter critically important research into politically charged fields like climate change\".<ref name=\":52\" /> The Judicial Watch lawsuit was inspired by Rep. [[Lamar Smith]] who accused the authors of the study of \"alter[ing] data\" to \"get the politically correct results they want.\"<ref name=\":52\" />\n\n=== Support for Breitbart News ===\nJudicial Watch has advertised for years on [[Breitbart News]], the far-right website formerly run by [[Steve Bannon]].<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/business/wp/2017/06/08/breitbart-lost-90-percent-of-its-advertisers-in-two-months-whos-still-there/|title=Breitbart lost 90 percent of its advertisers in two months: Who\u2019s still there?|last=Bhattarai|first=Abha|date=2017-06-08|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-12-25|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> The site was defended by Fitton against calls for advertisers to drop them for advertising. Fitton stated, \"Liberal activists want to destroy Breitbart, but we won\u2019t be cowed\".<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Voter fraud ===\nFitton said about [[Voter impersonation (United States)|voter fraud]]: \"We have all heard about voter fraud and the attempts by liberal media organs like the&nbsp;''New York Times''&nbsp;and Ivory Tower academics to dismiss it as a nonexistent problem. But it is real, widespread, and substantial to the point that it can decide elections\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Clean House: Exposing Our Government's Secrets and Lies|last=Fitton|first=Tom|publisher=Threshold Editions|year=2016|isbn=978-1501137051|location=New York|page=117}}</ref> Fitton has alleged that hundreds of thousands of undocumented immigrants voted in the 2018 mid-term elections.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/05/28/resignation-texas-is-reminder-how-trumps-vote-fraud-claims-come-up-empty/|title=A resignation in Texas is a reminder of how Trump\u2019s vote-fraud claims come up empty|last=|first=|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> There is no evidence of widespread voter fraud in California or Texas.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/california/statements/2019/jun/24/donald-trump/pants-fire-trumps-latest-california-voter-fraud-cl/|title=Trump\u2019s latest California voter fraud claim is Pants on Fire|website=@politifact|language=en|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/24/politics/fact-check-trump-voter-fraud-california/index.html|title=Trump makes yet another false claim about California voter fraud|author=Daniel Dale|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2020, the day of the [[Iowa caucuses]] in the Democratic presidential primary, Fitton suggested that voter fraud was afoot in Iowa by falsely claiming that \u201ceight Iowa counties have more voter registrations than citizens old enough to register.\u201d Iowa's Secretary of State, Paul Pate, a member of the Republican Party, debunked Fitton's claim by linking to official voter registration data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2020/02/03/election-2020-iowa-caucus-problems/4618371002/|title=The misinformation campaign: Iowa SOS blasts Judicial Watch for insinuating voter fraud|last=Clayworth|first=Jason|website=Des Moines Register|language=en|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/02/03/conservatives-push-false-claims-voter-fraud-twitter-iowans-prepare-caucus/|title=Conservatives push false claims of voter fraud on Twitter as Iowans prepare to caucus|last=|first=|date=2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Russian interference in the 2016 election ===\n{{main|Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections}}\nIn 2017, Judicial Watch helped to stoke Republican attacks against Special Counsel [[Robert Mueller]]'s investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/no-longer-a-lonely-battle-how-the-campaign-against-the-mueller-probe-has-taken-hold/2017/12/24/441fc726-e5cb-11e7-a65d-1ac0fd7f097e_story.html|title=No longer a \u2018lonely battle\u2019: How the campaign against the Mueller probe has taken hold|last=Kranish|first=Michael|date=2017-12-24|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-03-19|last2=Barrett|first2=Devlin|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|last3=Demirjian|first3=Karoun}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/08/07/trump-mueller-attack-judicial-watch-765081|title='I know that he listens to Tom': Meet Trump's anti-Mueller ally|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en}}</ref> He has referred to the Mueller probe as a \"coup\" against Trump.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/apr/29/donald-trump/was-donald-trump-target-coup-no/|title=Was Donald Trump the target of a coup? No|website=@politifact|language=en|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-twitter-video-removed-deleted-2020-russia-mueller-batman-a8862816.html|title=Trump has video removed after rambling late-night Twitter storm about conspiracy theories and immigrants|date=2019-04-10|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> Trump retweeted Fitton's remarks about a coup; PolitiFact rated the assertion that the Mueller probe was a coup as \"pants-on-fire\" false.<ref name=\":2\" /> Trump frequently listens to Fitton and had mentioned Fitton at least five times in his tweets by August 2018, including a promotion of an upcoming Fitton appearance on Fox.<ref name=\":0\" /> According to ''Politico'', \"Fitton\u2019s rhetoric is often indistinguishable from Trump\u2019s.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Fitton called for the Special Counsel investigation to be shut down, arguing that prosecutors in the probe were too biased against President Trump to conduct a credible investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/republicans-hammer-mueller-fbi-as-russia-investigation-intensifies/2017/12/06/4a6097ca-dabb-11e7-b1a8-62589434a581_story.html|title=Republicans hammer Mueller, FBI as Russia investigation intensifies|last=Barrett|first=Devlin|date=2017-12-06|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-03-19|last2=Sullivan|first2=Sean|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Fitton furthermore called for shutting down the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)]] \"because it was turned into a KGB-type operation by the Obama administration.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/364868-conservative-watchdog-head-we-need-to-consider-shutting-down-the-fbi|title=Conservative watchdog head: Do we need to shut down the FBI?|last=Anapol|first=Avery|date=December 14, 2017|newspaper=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/us/politics/trump-blames-justice-department-and-fbi-for-conduct-he-says-was-a-disgrace.html|title=Trump Calls Justice Department and F.B.I. Conduct \u2018a Disgrace\u2019|last=Davis|first=Julie Hirschfeld|date=2018-02-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-03-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> ''Newsweek'' rated the claim \"false\", stating that \"there is no comparison between the FBI and KGB.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/fact-check-did-fbi-become-kgb-type-operation-under-obama-748144|title=We fact-checked a Fox News guest's claim that Obama turned the FBI into the KGB|date=2017-12-14|work=Newsweek|access-date=2017-12-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]], Trump's former personal attorney, [[Criminal charges brought in the Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|pleaded guilty to crimes]] brought to light by Special Counsel Robert Mueller's probe in December 2018, Fitton dismissed the importance of the crimes. Fitton said it was \"weak tea\" and intended \"to make President Trump look bad.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/12/conservative-response-michael-cohen-guilty-plea|title=\"It's Weak Tea\": For MAGA Super-Fans, Trump's Legal Nightmare is more fake news|last=Nguyen|first=Tina|date=December 12, 2018|work=Vanity Fair|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Coronavirus pandemic, 2020 ===\nDuring the coronavirus pandemic, Fitton called on President Trump to \"reopen\" the United States amid social distancing and lockdowns to prevent spread of the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/conservative-medias-new-coronavirus-plan-reopen-the-country|title=Conservative Media\u2019s New Coronavirus Plan: Reopen The Country, No Matter Who Dies|website=BuzzFeed News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Fitton criticized Dr. [[Anthony Fauci]], the White House's leading epidemiology expert, and amplified right-wing conspiracy theories about Fauci.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/as-trump-signals-readiness-to-break-with-experts-his-online-base-assails-fauci/2020/03/26/3802de14-6df6-11ea-aa80-c2470c6b2034_story.html|title=As Trump signals readiness to break with experts, his online base assails Fauci|date=2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Singh|first=Maanvi|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/01/dr-fauci-security-reportedly-expanded-as-infectious-disease-expert-faces-threats|title=Dr Fauci: security reportedly expanded as infectious disease expert faces threats|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/490725-fauci-given-security-detail-after-receiving-threats|title=Fauci given security detail after receiving threats|last=Zilbermints|first=Regina|date=2020-04-01|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nFitton received the [[American Conservative Union]]'s 'Defender of the Constitution Award' during its annual [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in 2015.<ref>{{cite press release |author=Ross Hemminger |title=Tom Fitton Presented with the Defender of the Constitution Award  |url=http://conservative.org/tom-fitton-presented-with-the-defender-of-the-constitution-award/|location=National Harbor, MD |publisher=American Conservative Union |date=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book|last=Fitton|first=Tom|date=2014|title=The Corruption Chronicles: Obama's Big Secrecy, Big Corruption, and Big Government|isbn=978-1-4767-6705-5|publisher=Threshold Editions| location = New York}}\n* Fitton, Tom ''Clean House: Exposing Our Government's Secrets and Lies'' (New York: Threshold Editions, 2016).  {{ISBN|978-1-5011-3704-4}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.judicialwatch.org/ Judicial Watch homepage]\n* {{C-SPAN|tomfitton}}\n* [http://www.c-span.org/video/?286474-1/qa-tom-fitton Q & A with Tom Fitton, May 19, 2009]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitton, Tom}}\n\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:Columbian College of Arts and Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:People from West Nyack, New York]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n", "name_user": "66.8.205.94", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eVoter fraud:Removed false accusations)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Fitton"}
{"title_page": "Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf\n| fullname = D\u00fcsseldorfer Turn- und Sportverein<br>Fortuna 1895 e.V.\n| image = Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf.svg\n| image_size = 200\n| current = 2019\u201320 Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf season\n| nickname = Flingeraner, Fortunen, Rheinl\u00e4nder\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1895|5|5|df=yes}}\n| ground = [[Merkur Spiel-Arena]]\n| capacity = 54,600\n| chairman = Thomas R\u00f6ttgermann (President)<br>Erich Rutem\u00f6ller<br>[[Lutz Pfannenstiel]] \n| chrtitle = Board Members\n| manager = [[Uwe R\u00f6sler]]\n| mgrtitle = Head coach\n| league = [[Bundesliga]]\n| season = [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|2018\u201319]]\n| position = 10th\n| website = https://www.f95.de/home//\n| pattern_b1 = _fortuna1920h\n| pattern_la1 = _fortuna1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _fortuna1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = _fortuna1920h\n| pattern_so1 = _fortuna1920h\n| leftarm1 = FFFFFF\n| body1 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1 = FFFFFF\n| shorts1 = FFFFFF\n| socks1 = FFFFFF\n| pattern_b2 = _fortuna1920a\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = _fortuna1920a\n| leftarm2 = FF0000\n| body2 = \n| rightarm2 = FF0000\n| shorts2 = FF0000\n| socks2 = FF0000\n| pattern_b3 = _fortuna1920t\n| pattern_la3 = _fortuna1920t\n| pattern_ra3 = _fortuna1920t\n| pattern_sh3 = _fortuna1920t\n| pattern_so3 = _fortuna1920t\n| leftarm3 = 000000\n| body3 = 000000\n| rightarm3 = 000000\n| shorts3 = 000000\n| socks3 = 000000\n}}\n'''Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf''' ({{IPA-de|f\u0254\u0281\u02c8tu\u02d0na \u02c8d\u028fsl\u0329d\u0254\u0281f|pron|De-Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf.ogg}}) is a [[Football in Germany|German football club]] in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]. Founded in 1895, Fortuna entered the league in 1913 and was a fixture in the top flight from the early 1920s up to the creation of the [[Bundesliga]] in 1963. 2019\u201320 is their 25th season in the Bundesliga and the second in a row since getting promoted from the 2. Bundesliga in the 2017\u201318 season.\n\n==History==\n===Foundation to World War II===\nThe earliest roots of the association go back to the establishment of the gymnastics club Turnverein Flingern on 5 May 1895 in the village of [[Flingern]], today one of the eastern quarters of D\u00fcsseldorf. Two other sides figure in the club's early history: D\u00fcsseldorfer Fu\u00dfballklub Spielverein, founded in 1908, and FK Alemania 1911, which was founded in 1911 and became Fortuna 1911 the following year. In mid-1913, these two clubs merged to form D\u00fcsseldorfer Fu\u00dfball-Club Fortuna 1911 which played its debut season in the Westdeutschen Spielverband in 1913\u201314. TV Flingern joined Fortuna to create D\u00fcsseldorfer Turn- und Sportverein Fortuna on 15 November 1919.<ref name=\"Gr\u00fcne, Hardy 2001\">Gr\u00fcne, Hardy (2001). Vereinslexikon. Kassel: AGON Sportverlag {{ISBN|3-89784-147-9}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1920s, Fortuna won its first honours as a first tier side; it captured a district level Bezirksliga title in 1927, sent its first representative to the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]] in 1928 ([[Ernst Albrecht (footballer)|Ernst Albrecht]]), and took a second Bezirksliga title in 1929. The team continued to perform well into the 1930s, winning its third and fourth district titles en route to a [[Western German football championship]] in 1931 and its greatest success, a [[German football championship]] in 1933 against [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]], which was on the verge of becoming the era's dominant side in Germany. Fortuna was the first team to win the title without conceding a goal in the final rounds of the tournament. It beat [[Vorw\u00e4rts-Rasensport Gleiwitz]] (9\u20130), [[Arminia Hannover]] (3\u20130), [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] (4\u20130) and finally Schalke 04 (3\u20130) en route to becoming the first national champion from the industrial [[Rhine-Ruhr]] area.\n\nIn the following season, the club began playing in [[Gauliga Niederrhein]], 1 of 16 top-flight divisions formed in the re-organization of German football under the [[Third Reich]]. D\u00fcsseldorf dominated the division through the 1930s as five-time champions between 1936 and 1940, and made losing appearances in the national championship final in 1936 (1\u20132 to [[1. FC N\u00fcrnberg]]) and the final of the Tschammerpokal, the predecessor of today's [[DFB-Pokal]], in 1937 (1\u20132 against Schalke 04). The club was [[Promotion and relegation|relegated]] in 1942 but made a prompt return to the top flight the following season. In 1944\u201345, it began play as the combined wartime side Kriegsspielgemeinschaft TSV Fortuna/SC 99 D\u00fcsseldorf with partner D\u00fcsseldorfer Sport Club 1899, but took part in only two matches as [[Nazi Germany]] fell before the advance of Allied armies.<ref>Gr\u00fcne, Hardy (1996). Vom Kronprinzen bis zur Bundesliga. Kassel: AGON Sportverlag {{ISBN|3-928562-85-1}}</ref>\n\nThe most notable players of that era were [[Paul Janes]], Germany's most capped player from 1942 to 1970 (71 caps), German team captain (1939\u20131942) and member of the Breslau Eleven that beat [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] 8\u20130 in [[Breslau]] in 1937 and went on to win 10 of 11 games played during that year; [[Stanislaus Kobierski]], who earned 26 caps and scored Germany's first ever [[FIFA World Cup]] goal; [[Ernst Albrecht (footballer)|Ernst Albrecht]]; and [[Jakob Bender]].\n\n===Post War era===\n[[File:Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf Performance Chart.png|260px|thumb|Historical chart of Fortuna league performance after WWII]]\nAfter [[World War II]], Allied occupation authorities ordered the dissolution of all sports organizations in Germany. Fortuna was re-formed in 1945 and then played most of their football in the [[Oberliga West]] (I) in the years between 1947 and the creation of the [[Bundesliga]], Germany's professional football league, in 1963. It played as a lower-to-mid-table side but did earn three appearances in the DFB-Pokal final in&nbsp;\u2013 1957, 1958 and 1962&nbsp;\u2013 but was not able to take the prize, losing each of those matches to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], [[VfB Stuttgart]] and 1. FC N\u00fcrnberg. It was also during this era that [[Toni Turek]], goalkeeper for Germany's \"Miracle of Bern\" side at the [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954 World Cup]]; [[Erich Juskowiak]] (30 caps and World Cup player in [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]]); and later national team coach [[Jupp Derwall]] all represented Fortuna.\n\n===1960s and 1970s===\nFortuna's performance was not good enough to earn them a place among the original 16 teams chosen for the newly founded Bundesliga in 1963, but the club did manage to play its way into the premier division three years later for a cameo appearance in [[1966\u201367 Bundesliga|1966\u201367]]. Despite a sensational 2\u20131 away win at recently crowned [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]] winners [[Borussia Dortmund]] in its Bundesliga debut, Fortuna was immediately relegated, though only to return in 1971 for a stay that lasted 16 seasons and included two third-place league finishes (in [[1972\u201373 Bundesliga|1972\u201373]] and [[1973\u201374 Bundesliga|1973\u201374]]). On 9 December 1978, Fortuna recorded a 7\u20131 victory against Bayern Munich, to date the highest away defeat for Bayern in its entire Bundesliga history. In addition, Fortuna continued its prosperous play in the DFB-Pokal, making another three appearances. After losing in its fifth appearance in the final in [[1978 DFB-Pokal Final|1978]] against local rivals [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] (0\u20132), the club finally broke through and came away as champions in [[1979 DFB-Pokal Final|1979]], prevailing 1\u20130 against [[Hertha BSC]], then repeating as champions [[1980 DFB-Pokal Final|1980]] with 2\u20131 victory against 1. FC K\u00f6ln. During this period, the club established a record for consecutive DFB-Pokal match victories, with 18-straight between 1978 and 1981.\n\nFortuna is among a group of four teams which have made frequent appearances in the DFB-Pokal final only to come away empty-handed. Like [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]], Fortuna has just two wins against fives losses. 1. FC K\u00f6ln has four wins and six losses in the Cup final, while Schalke 04 has been frustrated most often, with five wins and seven losses. Four of the D\u00fcsseldorfer's losses were by a single goal and two of those were in extra time.\n\nThe club's best turn in European competition was in the [[1979 European Cup Winners' Cup Final]], where it finished as runners-up to [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], losing 4\u20133 in extra time in an exciting finale at [[Basel]]. It was the first of four occasions that the Catalan club won the tournament.\n\nFortuna achieved its success mostly with hometown players like the famous Allofs brothers ([[Klaus Allofs]] and [[Thomas Allofs]]) or players like [[Gerd Zewe]] (440 games in the Bundesliga), [[Dieter Herzog]], [[Reiner Geye]], [[Wolfgang Seel]] and [[Rudi Bommer]] who joined the team as nearly unknown players and ended as internationals. Between 1960 and 1967, [[Peter Meyer (footballer)|Peter Meyer]] scored 119 goals in 174 games.\n\n===1980s to the new century===\n[[File:LTU arena - Warsteiner.jpg|thumb|right|Esprit arena in D\u00fcsseldorf. View from the Warsteiner Trib\u00fcne. Match: Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf vs. [[FC St. Pauli]].]]\nSince its relegation in 1987, Fortuna has bounced back and forth between leagues, spending five more seasons in the Bundesliga in 1989\u201392 and 1995\u201397 and slipping as low as [[Oberliga Nordrhein]] (IV) in 2002\u201304. In 2001, the club escaped relegation to tier IV only because two other clubs were denied licenses to play in tier III for financial reasons. Fortuna had its own money problems at the time but have since managed to arrange its finances more or less back into order. Between 2001 and 2003, the club was sponsored by German punk rock band [[Die Toten Hosen]].<ref name=\"FAZ-online article\">{{cite web|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/sport/fussball-tote-hosen-steigen-mit-million-bei-fortuna-duesseldorf-ein-124221.html|title=\"Tote Hosen\" steigen mit Million bei Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf ein|website=faz.net|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Recent seasons===\nIn [[2008\u201309 3. Liga|2008\u201309]], Fortuna competed in the newly established [[3. Liga]], finishing second and gaining automatic promotion to the [[2. Bundesliga]], where it finished fourth in its comeback season, [[2009\u201310 2. Bundesliga|2009\u201310]]. In this season, Fortuna was the only side unbeaten in home-matches in the three top German (nationwide) leagues.\n\nAfter a promising 2009\u201310 season, the [[2010\u201311 2. Bundesliga|2010\u201311 season]] began poorly for Fortuna. After the first six games of the season, the club was in last place, having lost every match. During these first six matches, the club managed to score only two goals&nbsp;\u2013 one of which was an own-goal by the other side. Despite this discouraging start, Fortuna bounced back and finished the season in seventh place. [[2011\u201312 2. Bundesliga|2011\u201312]] began very differently: after the first half of the season, Fortuna was in first place in the table with a remarkable record of 12 wins, 5 draws and 0 losses. The \"Herbstmeister\" title gave the team and the fans hope that this could be the year Fortuna returned to the Bundesliga. The second half of the season was more challenging, as Fortuna was unable to maintain its pace: it suffered four losses and a number of draws, slipping to third place in the final standings. Nonetheless, this was sufficient for them to qualify for the two-game relegation playoff against the third-last place team in the Bundesliga&nbsp;\u2013 Hertha BSC. The first game of the relegation was played on 10 May 2012 in [[Berlin]], with Fortuna winning 2\u20131. Fortuna drew the deciding game which was played on 15 May in D\u00fcsseldorf. Hertha fans, however, threw firecrackers at the field and the players, and one minute before the match ended, overexcited Fortuna fans stormed the field.\n\nThe promotion to the Bundesliga represented an extraordinary personal achievement for team captain [[Andreas Lambertz]], as he became the first player in German football history to be promoted three times with the same club, from the then fourth-tier Oberliga to the Bundesliga. For striker [[Sascha R\u00f6sler]], it marked the fourth time in his career that he was promoted from the Second Division into the Bundesliga.\n\nComing with the recent promotion, the club achieved a new record in German football history, becoming the only German club that has been relegated from the Bundesliga down to a fourth-tier league (time period of downfall: 1997\u20132002) and promoted back to the Bundesliga afterwards (time period of uprising: 2004\u20132012).\n\nFortuna started the [[2012\u201313 Bundesliga]] season strongly: after five games, it was in fifth place in the table<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2012-13/5/0/spieltag.html|title=1. Bundesliga 2012/13, der 5. Spieltag|first=kicker online, N\u00fcrnberg|last=Germany|website=kicker online|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> and concerns about relegation seemed to have been put to rest. However, Fortuna's 1\u20130 home win over [[SpVgg Greuther F\u00fcrth]] on 16 February would prove to be the club's final victory of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2012-13/fortuna-duesseldorf-13/vereinstermine.html|title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf \u2013 Alle Termine der Saison 2012/13|first=kicker online, N\u00fcrnberg|last=Germany|website=kicker online|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> The season concluded with Fortuna playing in [[Hannover 96]], a match Fortuna lost 0\u20133. This defeat, combined with an [[FC Augsburg]] win over Greuther F\u00fcrth and a bizarre and unlikely victory by [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]] over second-place Borussia Dortmund, resulted in Fortuna dropping two places.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rp-online.de/sport/fussball/fortuna/ansatz-des-gut-spielens-zu-hoch-angesiedelt-aid-1.3408379|title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf: 'Ansatz des gut Spielens zu hoch angesiedelt'|first=RP|last=ONLINE|website=RP ONLINE|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> ''Fortuna'' finished 17th and were again relegated back to the 2. Bundesliga.\n\nFortuna's relegation was the result not only of this unlikely series of occurrences on the final day of the season, but also a poor conclusion to the year. Of its final eight matches, it did not win a single one; just one win would have secured its position for the following season's Bundesliga. This poor performance contributed to the dismissal of head coach [[Norbert Meier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rp-online.de/politik/fortuna-duesseldorf-trennt-sich-von-trainer-meier-aid-1.3428158|title=D\u00fcsseldorf: Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf trennt sich von Trainer Meier|first=RP|last=ONLINE|website=RP ONLINE|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nRelegation to the 2. Bundesliga led to a period of generally disappointing performance. Fortuna spent the years between 2013 and 2017 in the middle of the table, often battling against relegation and rarely challenging for promotion back to the Bundesliga. During these years, the club went through a series of coaching changes, with Oliver Reck, Frank Kramer, and former player Mike Buskens among others leading the club at various points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/fortuna-duesseldorf/9/|title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf - Manager history|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> Success however remained elusive.\n\nIn March 2016, Friedhelm Funkel \u2013 a native of Neuss \u2013 took over as coach of Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf. In his first game as coach, Funkel led the club to a 4\u20133 win against 1. FC Kaiserslautern, ending a month-long winless streak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/2bundesliga/spieltag/2-bundesliga/2015-16/27/2855675/spielanalyse_fortuna-duesseldorf-13_1-fc-kaiserslautern-37.html|title=Funkels Deb\u00fct gelingt \u2013 Nummer f\u00fcnf f\u00fcr F\u00fcnfst\u00fcck: Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf \u2013 1. FC Kaiserslautern 4:3 (3:1)|first=kicker online, N\u00fcrnberg|last=Germany|website=kicker online}}</ref> Funkel's start as coach marked the beginning of a period of increased stability and success for Fortuna.\n\nAt the start of the 2017\u201318 season, two of Fortuna's strongest performers from the previous year, goalkeeper Michael Rensing and forward Ihlas Bebou, were both lost from the club with Rensing suffering two broken ribs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rp-online.de/sport/fussball/fortuna/fortuna-duesseldorf-torwart-michael-rensing-ist-noch-immer-verletzt-aid-1.7378435|title=Fortuna-Torwart Rensing: 'Ich habe keinen Zeitdruck'|first=Falk|last=Janning|website=RP ONLINE}}</ref> and Bebou transferring to Bundesliga side Hannover 96.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bild.de/sport/fussball/hannover-96/bebou-klar-kent-wechsel-geplatzt-53053432,la=de.bild.html|title=Ihlas Bebou wechselt nach Hannover 96 \u2013 Transfer von Ryan Kent platzt}}</ref> A further setback was that Funkel's assistant Peter Hermann asked to be released from his contract with Fortuna in order to rejoin his mentor Jupp Heynckes upon his return to FC Bayern.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/sport/fussball/bayern-muenchen-jupp-heynckes-peter-hermann-bittet-um-freigabe-a-1171563.html|title=Heynckes-Wunschassistent Hermann: Ja, er will|date=6 October 2017|work=Der Spiegel}}</ref> With these three losses, it appeared that the 2017\u201318 season could be difficult for Fortuna. However, the club started extremely strongly: on the fourth day of the season, Fortuna had climbed to first place in the table, with a draw and three wins. For the remainder of the year, they would not drop below third place, benefiting from particularly strong play by Rensing's replacement in goal, Raphael Wolf, newly-acquired Belgian forward Benito Raman, striker Rouwen Hennings, and midfielder Florian Neuhaus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/2bundesliga/vereine/2-bundesliga/2017-18/fortuna-duesseldorf-13/chart-saisonvergleich.html|title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf \u2013 der Verlauf der 2017/18 im interaktiven Chart|first=kicker online, N\u00fcrnberg|last=Germany|website=kicker online}}</ref> A late-season slump saw Fortuna lose three games in succession in early April, but Fortuna won their next two matches, securing promotion to the Bundesliga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rp-online.de/sport/fussball/fortuna/aufstieg-2018-von-fortuna-duesseldorf-durch-21-bei-dynamo-dresden-aid-1.7542530|title=2:1-Sieg in Dresden: Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf ist zur\u00fcck in der Bundesliga!|first=Bernd|last=Jolitz|website=RP ONLINE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rp-online.de/sport/fussball/fortuna/aufstieg-fortuna-duesseldorf-und-der-historische-28-april-2018-aid-1.7545132|title='Wir steigen auf, und K\u00f6ln steigt ab': Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf und der historische 28. April|first=Bernd Jolitz|last=Dresden|website=RP ONLINE}}</ref> In the final game of the season, with promotion already secured, Fortuna defeated 1. FC N\u00fcrnberg 3:2 on a last-minute goal thereby securing first place and the 2. Division Championship. For coach Friedhelm Funkel, this marks the sixth time he had led a club to promotion\u2014a German record.\n\nFortuna D\u00fcsseldorf's return to first-division football in 2018\u201319 was greeted with great enthusiasm by their supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rp-online.de/sport/fussball/fortuna/|title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf Nachrichten|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> The first half of the season was marked by strong but inconsistent play.<ref name=\"Termine18/19\" /> Fortuna played remarkably well against top Bundesliga sides, taking a point from Leipzig and defeating Hoffenheim and first-place Borussia Dortmund.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.de/fussball/bundesliga/2018-2019/fortuna-dusseldorf-borussia-dortmund-12-herbstmeister-bvb-patzt_sto7057903/story.shtml|title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf - Borussia Dortmund: 1:2! Herbstmeister BVB patzt|website=eurosport.de|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> Most encouraging was an away draw against the defending champions Bayern Munich, when Fortuna came back after trailing 2\u20130 and 3\u20131, to secure a 3\u20133 draw in the 93rd minute, with [[Dodi Lukebakio]] scored all three of Fortuna's goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rp-online.de/sport/fussball/fortuna/fortuna-duesseldorf-dodi-lukebakio-sorgt-beim-fc-bayern-muenchen-fuer-eine-sternstunde_aid-34693267|title=Lukebakio beschert Fortuna-Fans eine Sternstunde|website=rponline.de|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> However, Fortuna failed to play with the same consistency and decisiveness against clubs lower in the table, against whom they will battle to avoid relegation, losing to Augsburg, N\u00fcrnberg and Mainz, and only managing a draw against Stuttgart.<ref name=\"Termine18/19\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2018-19/fortuna-duesseldorf-13/vereinstermine.html|title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf Vereinstermine|website=kicker.de|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf entered the mid-winter break in 14th place in the table, concluding the first half of the season with three successive wins against Freiburg, Dortmund and Hannover.<ref name=\"Termine18/19\" />\n\n==Sponsorship==\nFor the 2017/18 season, online sports betting website [[Tipbet]] renewed its agreement as Premium Partners of Fortuna.<ref>{{cite web|last1=News|first1=SBC|title=SBC|url=http://www.sbcnews.co.uk/football/2016/07/14/tipbet-renews-fortuna-dusseldorf-premium-partnership-with-fortuna-dusseldorf/|publisher=SBC News|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> The deal involves marketing campaigns to raise brand awareness, while regular promotions are organised.<ref name=\"Tipbet\">{{cite web|last1=Sports betting|first1=Tipbet|title=Tipbet Sports Odds|url=https://www.tipbet.com/en/content/fortuna-dusseldorf|website=Tipbet|publisher=Tipbet|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Players==\n{{For2|recent transfers|[[List of German football transfers summer 2019#Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf|Transfers summer 2019]]|[[List of German football transfers winter 2019\u201320#Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf|Transfers winter 2019\u201320]]}}\n===Current squad===\n{{updated|1 February 2020|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.f95.de/profis/team/kader/|title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf 1895: Kader|trans-title=Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf 1895: Squad|language=German|website=f95.de|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|pos=GK|nat=GER|name=[[Michael Rensing]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 3|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Andr\u00e9 Hoffmann (footballer)|Andr\u00e9 Hoffmann]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|pos=DF|nat=GHA|name=[[Kasim Nuhu]]|other=on loan from [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 5|pos=DF|nat=TUR|name=[[Kaan Ayhan]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 6|pos=MF|nat=USA|name=[[Alfredo Morales]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 7|pos=MF|nat=GER|name=[[Oliver Fink]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 8|pos=MF|nat=GER|name=[[Aymen Barkok]]|other=on loan from [[Eintracht Frankfurt]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|pos=FW|nat=POL|name=[[Dawid Kownacki]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|pos=MF|nat=KVX|name=[[Valon Berisha]]|other=on loan from [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|pos=MF|nat=TUR|name=[[Kenan Karaman]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|pos=DF|nat=POL|name=[[Adam Bodzek]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|3rd captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|pos=MF|nat=GHA|name=[[Kelvin Ofori]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|pos=MF|nat=GER|name=[[Erik Thommy]]|other=on loan from [[VfB Stuttgart]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|pos=MF|nat=GER|name=[[Thomas Pledl]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|pos=DF|nat=DEN|name=[[Mathias J\u00f8rgensen]]|other=on loan from [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|pos=FW|nat=GER|name=[[Steven Skrzybski]]|other=on loan from [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|pos=MF|nat=AUT|name=[[Kevin St\u00f6ger]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Niko Gie\u00dfelmann]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|pos=GK|nat=USA|name=[[Zack Steffen]]|other=on loan from [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Matthias Zimmermann (footballer, born 1992)|Matthias Zimmermann]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=26|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Diego Contento]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=27|pos=FW|nat=GHA|name=[[Opoku Ampomah]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=28|pos=FW|nat=GER|name=[[Rouwen Hennings]]|other=[[Captain (association football)#Vice-captain|vice-captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=29|pos=DF|nat=AUT|name=[[Markus Suttner]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|pos=GK|nat=GER|name=[[Raphael Wolf]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=31|pos=MF|nat=GER|name=[[Marcel Sobottka]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=32|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Robin Bormuth]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=33|pos=GK|nat=GER|name=[[Florian Kastenmeier]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=37|pos=FW|nat=GHA|name=[[Bernard Tekpetey]]|other=on loan from [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=38|pos=GK|nat=GER|name=[[Tim Wiesner]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=39|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Jean Zimmer]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=40|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[Johannes B\u00fchler]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Out of squad===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|pos=GK|nat=GER|name=Jannick Thei\u00dfen}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=Georgios Siadas}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Out on loan===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|pos=MF|nat=CRO|name=[[Davor Lovren]]|other=at [[NK Slaven Belupo|Slaven Belupo]] until 30 June 2020}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|pos=DF|nat=GER|name=[[G\u00f6khan G\u00fcl]]|other=at [[SV Wehen Wiesbaden|Wehen Wiesbaden]] until 30 June 2020}